<a href="../article/adoption.shtml"><img src="../adopted.gif" alt="[Problem Adopted Children]" align=bottom border=0 width=142 height=33></a> <a href="../article/seizures.shtml"><img src="../seizures.gif" alt="[Seizures in Asthmatic Children]" align=bottom border=0 width=142 height=33></a></p>
<h3><a href="../index.html">The Consumer Law Page</a>: <a href="index.html">Brochures</a>:</h3>
<hr>
</body>

</html>
</p>
<h3>Facts for Consumers from the Federal Trade Commission</h3>
<h2>Mobile Radio Investment Scams -- January 1994</h2>
<p>Television commercials, program-length infomercials, and newspaper ads throughout the country have touted the high profits to 
be made from investing in Specialized Mobile Radio systems (SMR) or from licenses to operate these systems. Some ads 
promote SMRs as an alternative to cellular telephone systems. SMR refers to a set of radio frequencies or channels allocated by 
the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) primarily to transmit and receive paging, data communications, and voice 
transmission -- such as radio dispatch and mobile telephone -- over distances of less than 40 miles. The FCC issues licenses for 
SMR systems consisting of one or more channel pairs.</p>
<p>SMR systems have significant technological limitations that may hamper their commercial competitiveness with cellular telephone 
systems. Prospective investors should consider some limiting aspects of SMR systems as telephone systems. First, a 
conventional SMR system must be combined with other SMR systems into a network to achieve sufficient transmission capacity. 
In addition, to compete with the call-carrying capacity of cellular telephone systems, an SMR would have to be upgraded with 
more advanced digital equipment that could cost in excess of several million dollars. Further, most SMR systems use &quot;analog&quot; 
technology which, among other things, limits an SMR channel to a single user at a time, much like the old-fashioned telephone 
&quot;party line.&quot; This could result in a higher percentage of &quot;busy signals&quot; than a user would encounter on a cellular system. Another 
limitation of analog technology is the lack of compatibility of SMR equipment made by different manufacturers.</p>
<p>This could result in breaks in call transmission when customers &quot;roam&quot; into neighboring service areas. This also may make it 
difficult for SMR license holders to guarantee call services to customers once they travel beyond the immediate SMR provider's 
service area.</p>
<h4>SMR License Scams</h4>
<p>Telemarketers are soliciting consumers to invest thousands of dollars to purchase a government license to operate an SMR 
system. However, for between $250 and $1,000 -- including the $35 FCC application fee and legal expenses -- individuals can 
apply for an SMR license directly from the FCC. Licenses are granted on a &quot;first-come, first-serve&quot; basis and, according to the 
FCC, are available in many areas of the country.</p>
<h4>SMR Network Scams</h4>
<p>In a related scheme, telemarketers also are soliciting consumers to invest in partnerships to develop a network of SMR systems 
to compete with cellular telephone services. Some telemarketers have promised investors annual returns of several thousand 
dollars per year within 18 months of the startup of the network.</p>
<p>Given the significant technological limitations of SMR systems, such profits are unlikely due to the high costs of upgrading the 
system with digital equipment to compete &quot;head-on&quot; with cellular and other large SMR operators.</p>
<h4>Tips for Investors</h4>
<p>Before investing in an SMR partnership, consider taking the following steps to help protect yourself:</p>
<p>Find out the specific location of the proposed SMR license, system, or network. Beware of any company that refuses to provide 
this information.</p>
<p>Verify that the proposed location contains enough users to support an SMR telephone system.</p>
<p>Conduct a financial analysis of the project. Include projections for start-up costs, operating capital, cash flow, and income.</p>
<p>Investigate the financial representations made by the salesperson and ask questions. Consider getting advice concerning the 
viability of the investment from your attorney, accountant, or other business professional.</p>
<p>Be skeptical of a company that promotes partnerships as a way to put SMR networks in operation. Such partnerships may not 
comply with state securities laws. Check with your state securities agency.</p>
<p>Be cautious of a telemarketing company that promises to build and manage an SMR system. You should verify whether the 
company has the technical and business expertise to do so. Also, under FCC rules, a licensee must be actively involved in the 
management of the business or the license may be revoked.</p>
<p>Be suspicious of any company that claims that an SMR license may be sold immediately after being granted. The FCC prohibits 
the sale of a license until the license is placed in operation.</p>
<h4>For More Information</h4>
<p>If you have questions about Specialized Mobile Radio systems or the license-application process, write: Federal 
Communications Commission, Private Radio Bureau, 2025 M Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20554.</p>
<p>If you have a complaint about an application-preparation service for SMR licenses or SMR network investments, write: 
Correspondence Branch, Federal Trade Commission, Washington, D.C. 20580. You also can contact the National Fraud 
Information Center at 1-800-876-7060 (9:00 a.m. - 5:30 p.m., EST, Monday - Friday).</p>
<p>For a list of all the FTC's consumer and business publications, contact: Public Reference, Federal Trade Commission, 
Washington, D.C. 20580; 202-326-2222. Ask for a free copy of Best Sellers.</p>
<p>FTC CONSUMER &amp; SMALL BUSINESS ADVISORY - PUBLIC DOCUMENT</p>
