<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - EMPLOYMENT SERVICES</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>AACI Employment Services</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>inding satisfactory employment is a key to successful 
aliyah.  AACI plays an important role in the oleh's job search and 
professional growth in Israel, and also assists potential olim in 
planning their aliyah.<P>
AACI maintains a computerized data base of contacts, referrals 
and job listings in over 90 categories;  new information is entered 
daily and all material is regularly renewed and updated.  This data 
base is the foundation for the employment services offered.<P>
<STRONG>PRE-ALIYAH EMPLOYMENT SERVICES</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>J</FONT>ob Developers arrange individual Pilot Trips 
for potential olim who come to explore employment opportunities prior to 
their aliyah.  This service includes circulation of resumes, appointments 
with employers, networking meetings with North American professionals, 
and counseling sessions with AACI Regional Counselors regarding olim 
rights, medical services, schools, etc.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>T</FONT>he Job Developers also respond to inquiries from 
abroad on employment subjects such as market trends,  licensing  and 
certification requirements, and networking options.<P>

AACI also provides up to date information on professions and employment 
opportunities to the Shlichim in the Israel Aliyah Centers in the 
US and Canada, including a periodic list of actual job openings taken 
from the Israeli press and AACI's own sources.<P>
<STRONG>SERVICES TO OLIM AND AACI MEMBERS</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>N</FONT>etworking is the key to discovering the "hidden 
job market".  AACI staff cultivate a wide network of employment contacts 
who are available to guide olim in their occupations, introduce them to 
potential employers and fellow professionals, take them to professional 
meetings, tell them about job openings, etc.  This information is 
provided to olim during individual counseling sessions with AACI 
Regional Counselors.<P>
AACI members are also referred to job openings listed with AACI 
through our contacts in various companies throughout Israel.<P>
AACI encourages the oleh to assume responsibility for his/her own 
job search.  Periodic workshops and regular counseling sessions focus 
on giving the oleh the tools and knowledge to conduct a successful 
job search by introducing him to the use of resource materials, 
directories, professional associations and journals.  Resume writing 
workshops and self-guided resume writing kits teach the oleh to write 
his/her own effective resume and to edit and revise an outdated one.  
Interviewing techniques are also reviewed and practiced when necessary.<P>
<STRONG>PROFESSIONAL GROUPS</STRONG><P>
AACI sponsors monthly Business Forums and Professional Networks 
throughout Israel, an opportunity for small business owners, the 
self-employed and other professionals to make important contacts, 
share experiences with others, "learn the ropes" and benefit from 
experts in their field.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>A</FONT> Computer Club meets monthly in Jerusalem, 
providing up to date computer related information to professionals 
and hobbyists and an opportunity to share job leads and developments 
in the field.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>A</FONT> women's professional network, a business and 
professional group meet monthly in Tel Aviv. Professional groups also 
meet regularly in Haifa  and Pardes Hannah area.

<FONT SIZE=+1>A</FONT>lthough AACI does not offer business advise, 
we do provide initial counseling and referrals fo those interested in 
starting their own business.
</UL>
