<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Finding an Apartment</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>Finding an Apartment</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center><P>
<H3>SOURCES</H3>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>

<LI><H4>REALTORS</H4><P>
Realtors will charge a fee - usually one month's rent for rental property 
and a percentage of the cost of property if purchased.<P>
If you work with more than one Realtor, you should avoid seeing the 
same property with two separate agents.  This would result in having 
to pay Realtors' fees to both agents.<P>

<LI><H4>COMPUTERIZED APARTMENT LISTINGS</H4>
There are two services in Jerusalem which will allow you access 
to their lists and provide you with periodic updates for a monthly fee.  
The lists provided will be based on the neighborhoods you are interested 
in and your budget.<P>

<OL TYPE=a, b, c, ...>
<LI>Shaal - 21 King George Street.  Tel: 02-6256919  Fax: 02-6254457
<LI>Ma'agar Meida - 5 Dorot HaRishonim.  Tel: 02-6253728  Fax: 02-6255424<P>
<LI>For realtor services in other cities contact your AACI regional office.
Please note:  The above do not have overseas services.
</OL><P>

<LI>NEWSPAPERS are a good source of apartment hunters.  The Hebrew 
press (especially  Kol ha'ir) generally has more ads of this type than 
the Jerusalem Post.<P>

<LI>Cities in Israel, some fairly large, still works on many levels 
like a small town.  Often apartment information can be gathered by 
asking neighborhood residents, grocery shop owners and by placing home 
made handbills in individual mailboxes.  Community bulletin boards can 
also give some good leads.  Check supermarkets and the university boards 
as well.<P>
</OL>

<H3>GENERAL ADVICE</H3>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI>Before renting or buying visit the neighborhood at various times 
of day and night - notice the noise levels, presence of children, 
gardens - and the general appearance of the neighborhood. To avoid 
future damage claims by owners include in the 

contract who is responsible for which repairs. Note the accessability 
of English speaking neighbors.<P>

<LI>Bruto refers to the total size of your apt. including porches, 
walls percentage of halls, elevators etc..  Netto 
refers to the actual living space of your apartment. These figures 
affect the amount of Arnona, municipal tax, paid.<P>
</OL>
Updated:  January 1996
</UL>

