<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Post Aliyah Checklist</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>AACI - Post Aliyah Checklist</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center><P>
<STRONG>Have you made an appointment with an AACI counselor?</STRONG><BR>
AACI is an organization of former Americans and Canadians ready to 
help and guide you.  AACI's aliyah counselors can assist you with 
both general aliyah issues and your individual concerns.<P>
<STRONG>Have you received your complimentary membership?</STRONG><BR>
All new olim from North America are entitled to a free initial three-month 
membership in AACI. Visit or call your local regional office and 
join today!<P>
<STRONG>Have you received your teudat oleh?</STRONG><BR>
Every newcomer must have a teudat oleh (immigrant certificate) to 
facilitate all absorption processes.  This document is usually issued 
upon arrival at the airport if you process your aliyah abroad through 
the Israel Aliyah Center in North America.  If you change your status 
in Israel, go to your local Ministry of Absorption office.<P>
<STRONG>For all official transactions, it is advisable to carry with 
you: passport photos, teudat oleh, passports of all family members 
and teudat zehut (identity card) and application form where 
required.</STRONG><P>
<STRONG>Have you received your teudat zehut?</STRONG><BR>
Every Israeli carries a teudat zehut (identity card), which is your 
I.D. in many daily transactions.  Apply for a teudat zehut at your 
local Ministry of Interior office.<P>
<STRONG>Have you received your Israeli driver's license?</STRONG><BR>
An Israeli driver's license is needed to clear your car from customs. 
Make sure you get your Israeli license soon after arrival.  Apply for one 
at your local licensing bureau.  Bring along a copy of your foreign 
driver's license, passport, 2 photos, teudat oleh plus results of 
an eye examination performed by a qualified optometrist in Israel.  
Senior citizens may be asked for a medical examination report.  A 
driving test is part of the procedure.<P>
<STRONG>Have you opened bank accounts as an oleh or temporary 
resident?</STRONG><BR>
Bank accounts should be opened immediately.  Many employers, 
as well as National Insurance (Bituach Leumi) pay directly into 
your shekel account.  Foreign currency cash and travelers' checks can 
be deposited only within 45 days of your arrival in Israel as an Oleh.<P>
<STRONG>Have you registered at Bituach Leumi?</STRONG><BR>
If you have any independent children under 18 living with you, you 
may be entitled to monthly payments from National Insurance 
(Bituach Leumi).  Bring you bank account number.<P>
<STRONG>Have you registered your children in school or kindergarten?
</STRONG><BR>
You can register your children for school and kindergarten at the 
local municipality or school registration office.  Bring birth 
certificates, teudot zehut of both parents, teudat oleh and proof 
of residence.  You must also know your children's Hebrew dates of birth.  
You may be asked for other documents as well.<P>
<STRONG>Have you investigated rent subsidies at a local 
mortgage bank?</STRONG><BR>
Most newcomers are entitled to a rent subsidy when renting on 
the open market.  Bring your teudat oleh, teudat zehut and money 
for fees when you visit the bank<P>
<STRONG>Have you taken advantage of your rights to buy locally 
made goods without tax?</STRONG><BR>
Newcomers can buy many locally made articles, including 
appliances, tax free.  Before paying, bring your teudat oleh and 
the purchase order from the retailer to the local customs office 
in order to receive a tax exemption slip.<P>
<STRONG>Have you arranged for your income tax reduction?</STRONG><BR>
As a newcomer you are entitled to a reduction on your income tax.  
To receive it, bring a letter from your employer to your local 
tax authority.  Some employers take care of this for you.<P>
<STRONG>Have you taken advantage of discounts and exemptions on 
municipal taxes (arnona)?</STRONG><BR>
Check with your AACI region or local municipality about benefits 
for olim in your area.<P>
<STRONG>Have you asked about special discounts and loans for 
olim?</STRONG><BR>
Ask AACI about discounts on municipal cultural activities, and TV 
tax exemption.Various AACI membership discounts and emergency loans<P>
<STRONG>Have you registered at a sick fund</STRONG><BR>
During their first 6 months of aliyah, olim will receive an exemption 
on their health tax provided that they are unemployed or their income 
is low.  Olim may receive an additional 6 months exemption if 
they are receiving living allowance "d'mei kiyum".  Olim should 
register at the kupah of their choice.   Temporary Residents 
should speak to an AACI counselor for information on registration 
and payments.<P>
<STRONG>Do you know the number of your local Magen David  
Adom?</STRONG><BR>
Israel's emergency first aid stations, Magen David Adom 
operate 24 hour emergency service.<P>

