<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Driving in Israel </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>DRIVING IN ISRAEL - 1996</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Driving in Israel without a valid drivers' license in illegal.</B><P>

A recent decision by the Israel Supreme Court has highlighted a problem affecting some drivers who may not be driving with an Israeli driver's license.  The drivers potentially affected included long-term tourists, academics on sabbatical, new immigrants, temporary residents, returning Israelis and possibly foreign diplomats, foreign clergy and UN personnel.
<P>
The law, as is presently interpreted, permits  new immigrants and temporary residents to drive in Israel with a foreign or international driver's license for no more than 3 months.  Beyond that they are permitted to drive only with an Israeli driver's license.  Other foreign residents, including tourists, who have resided in Israel for more than 1 year, (even if that year was interrupted by trips abroad), are also permitted to drive in Israel only with an Israeli driver's license.  Any other license is not valid for driving in Israel. 
<P>
It was previously understood by many, that regular interruptions of residence in Israel, which may suffice to maintain tourist status in Israel, would also allow one to continue to drive in Israel with a foreign or international driver's license.  The Bureau of Motor Vehicles, now gives tourists the option upon passing a practical (road) drivers' test of receiving an Israeli license.  This is only for tourists who are in the country for less than 3 years continously.  
<P>
The ramification of the law is that:
<ol>
<li>The insurance policies of drivers without a valid license are not in force.  Both the compulsory insurance which covers bodily injury to drivers, passengers and pedestrians as well as comprehensive and third party insurance which covers damage and loss related to cars and other property.
</ol><br>
Recommendations:
<p>
We recommend, therefore, to all new immigrants and temporary residents to apply for an Israeli drivers' license as soon as possible and to complete the procedure within the first three months of arrival in Israel.
<p>
If you are an immigrant or temporary resident who has been in Israel for more than 3 months, driving on anything other than an Israeli drivers' license is illegal.
<p>
For tourists who are planning to remain in Israel for more than 3 months,  we recommend that you obtain an Israeli license as soon as possible in order to be driving legally in Israel
<p>
<B>PROCEDURE FOR CONVERTING  LEVEL 2 DRIVER'S LICENSE FOR PRIVATE OR COMMERCIAL VEHICLES UP TO 4000 KGS.</B>
<p>
For holders of a valid foreign or international license an abbreviated application procedure applies.  Please note: converting a foreign driver's license does not require surrendering your foreign driver's license.
<ol>
<li>Go to your local Bureau of Motor Vehicles, with your valid non-Israeli license and photocopy (both sides), your teudat oleh and teudat zehut or passport and 2 passport photos.  (Returning Israelis may convert their license on condition that the foreign license was issued at least three months prior to entering Israel.)  Please note: you must meet the minimum age of 17 and 6 months.
<li>Fill out the application, receive authorization for conversion of a foreign license and receive a payment form.
<li>Take the payment form to any Post Office and pay the fee.
<li>Go to a certified optometrist or optician to take an eye test.  (There is no optometrist at the Bureau of Motor Vehicles.)   Some optometrists do not charge for this especially if you have purchased glasses there.  Senior Citizens require a medical exam as well; women from age 60, and men from age 65.  Forms for the examination may be obtained at all offices or branches of the Licensing Bureau.
<li>Take a minimum of one lesson with an driving instructor.  (Sometimes certain driving schools insist on at least two.)
<li>Schedule and take the practical examination (road test).  You must use a driving instructor's car for this.  You schedule the road test throughout the instructor.  The test may take place at any branch of the  Bureau .of Motor Vehicles (listed below).  Bring with you a) foreign driver's license + photocopy (both sides), b) eye test certificate,  c) teudet oleh and teudat zehut, d) foreign passport, e) 2 passport photos.  The road test is conducted by an examiner from the  Bureau of Motor Vehicles.
<li>If you do not pass the road test you may take it again. 
<li>If you do not pass the road test on the second try, you will be required to pass a theoretical examination (written test) as well as an additional road test.
<p>
Conversion of a foreign license to an Israeli license may be conducted at the following Licensing Bureaus: 
<p>
Rechov Yad Harutzim <BR>
Beit HaYatzranim<BR>
<BR>
 Jerusalem<BR>
Tel: 02-6783114<BR>
<BR>
Binyan Clal<BR>
 97 Jaffa Road<BR>
<BR>
Jerusalem<BR>
Tel: 02-6234433<BR>
<BR>
1 Rehov HaLochamim<BR>
 Tel HaGiborim<BR>
<BR>
Holon<BR>
Tel: 03-5027666<BR>
<BR>
Haifa Bay<BR>
Haifa<BR>
Tel: 04-8721351<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
20 Rehov Havdil<BR>
Emek Sarah Industrial Zone<BR>
<BR>
Beersheva<BR>
Tel: 07-6406111 <BR>
<BR>
 94 Rehov HaNasi<BR>
Ashkelon<BR>
 Tel: 07-734684<p>



Please check the above information with an AACI counselor.   Also, it is advisable to check with the above offices what their office hours are, and if there is an office closer to you.
<p>
We wish to thank Chaim Goldfus and Steven Kelter, of Goldfus & Assoc.
<br> AACINSURANCE Agents, for contributing to this article.  
For further information, you may reach Mr. Goldfus and Mr. Kelter at <br>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:kelter@pobox.com">kelter@pobox.com</A><br>
tel: 972-2-612223/4 <br>
fax: 972-2-612225<br>
Goldfus & Asssoc. 
9A Diskin St. 5h Fl., 
Jerusalem 96440, Israel.
<p>
<I>The information presented in this article was accurate a the time of its writing to the best of the knowledge of the authors.  <br>Changes in the law or its interpretation, and changes in bureaucratic procedures are possible.  Neither the authors, AACI or AACINSURANCE  take responsibility for the accuracy of the information provided herein.</I>

