<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Foreign Currency Regulations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>Foreign Currency Regulations</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1>February 1996</FONT></CENTER><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>I</FONT>srael has strict foreign currency controls, but 
there are exemptions for Olim, who are called "Ba'alei Ptor" 
(exemption holders).<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>or 30 years following the date of entry 
into Israel as a new immigrant or temporary resident (NI/TR) you can 
continue to hold assets abroad, and can also hold foreign currency 
in Israel and transfer unlimited foreign currency to and from Israel.  
This is done through a free foreign currency account in an authorized 
bank in Israel ("Patach").<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>I</FONT>nterest received in such an account is 
exempt from tax for the first 20 years.  From the 21st to the 30th 
year tax on interest is limited to 25%.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>oreign currency brought to Israel in cash by a 
NI/TR must be deposited at an authorized bank within 10 days of 
arrival in Israel (45 days if first entry).<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>A</FONT> NI/TR may use assets held prior to immigration to 
conduct business, and this includes using foreign currency.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>oreign currency legally converted into Shekels 
may be reconverted in the first 20 years after entry, provided at least 12 
months have passed since the original conversion.  The original bank 
documents showing the conversion into Shekels must be produced and 
surrendered to the bank.  From the 21st to the 30th year you can 
continue to operate your free foreign currency account, but can no 
longer buy back foreign currency against Shekel conversion receipts.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>P</FONT>assive income from abroad such as rents, interest 
or dividends, which is received directly in Israel is exempt from 
tax for the first seven years.  Thereafter it is taxable.  
It is very easy and quite legal to avoid this tax by simply having the 
passive income deposited in your account abroad.  Thereupon it 
becomes your money and when you write a check on your foreign account, 
you are making a non-taxable transfer of your own capital.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>A</FONT>t the end of the 30 year period, your free 
foreign currency account converts into an Israel resident's 
account.  Assets in foreign bank accounts or securities must 
be transferred to Israel (to an Israel resident's account).  Real property 
abroad owned prior to Aliyah or purchased during the 30 years may 
continue to be held.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>M</FONT>any Olim who are approaching the 30 year date 
set up trusts to divest themselves of legal ownership of assets so that 
they no longer control them and thus cannot be compelled to transfer 
them to Israel.<P>
<HR WIDTH=20% ALIGN=center>
AACI wishes to thank Yitzhak Heimowitz,  Attorney of Law  for writing this 
article.<BR>
Mr. Heimowitz can be contacted at:<BR> Tel:03-5601994  Fax:03-5605356<BR>
64A Shenkin St., Tel Aviv 61141<BR>
</UL>

