<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - National Health Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>NATIONAL HEALTH LAW - 1995-1996</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>D</FONT>ue to the confusion and varied information 
regarding the National Health Law and payments, we compiled the following 
information in an attempt to clarify the new changes.<P>
<STRONG>The National Health Law:</STRONG> Guarantees equal medical 
care to all residents of Israel regardless of their age and medical 
state, and guarantees the full basket of medical services.<P>
<STRONG>What Should You Do?</STRONG>  Anyone already a member of a 
Kupat Cholim is not required to re-register with a Kupat Cholim.  
If you are registered with more than one Kupat Cholim, you will be 
considered to be registered with the Kupat Cholim fund with which you 
last registered.  In an emergency, when a resident requires urgent 
medical treatment and is not registered, this resident will be 
entitled to receive medical health services from a Kupat Cholim 
determined by the Director General of the Ministry of Health.<P>
<STRONG>If You Are a Resident but Not a Member of Any Kupat Cholim:</STRONG>  
You will be registered with a Kupat Cholim chosen by the Ministry 
of Health.  After 6 months, you will be able to transfer in accordance 
with normal procedures.<P>
<STRONG>New Immigrants (olim):</STRONG>  Will receive an exemption on 
paying the health tax during their first six months of Aliyah provided 
that they are unemployed or that their income is not higher than 50% 
of the average pay.  New immigrants receiving pensions in Israel will 
start paying the health tax after six months free if they receive a 
living allowance (d'mei kiyum).<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>U</FONT>pon arrival in Israel, new immigrants will be 
provided with a medical insurance from which they should use to register at 
the Kupat Holim of their choice.<P>
<STRONG>Couples & Children:</STRONG>  Married may be registered 
with different Kupat Cholim.  Children under age 18 will be registered 
with the Kupat Cholim of the parents.<P>
<STRONG>Transferring to Another Sick Fund:</STRONG>  Anyone registered with 
a Kupat Cholim for at least one year is entitled to transfer to another 
Kupat Cholim. A transfer request may be submitted at any time, 
but transfers only come into effect once every 6 months (Jan. 
1st and July 1st).  Transfer Forms will be at the new Kupah that 
you wish to join.<P>
<STRONG>Supplementary Insurance:</STRONG>  May be offered by a Kupat 
Cholim for medical services not included in the basic services basket.  
Some of the Kupot have requested that their members not cancel their 
bank's standing order for supplementary insurance.  Call you Kupah 
to find out what their instructions are.<P>
<STRONG>Western Retirees:</STRONG>  For pensioners who are receiving 
Bituach Leumi allotments, your health insurance payments and 
pensions will be deducted from this.  For seniors not receiving Bituach 
Leumi payments, Bituach Leumi will be sending out an "igeret" (notice) 
in the mail telling them how to proceed.  If a notice does not arrive, 
contact Bituach Leumi.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>I</FONT>ncome from abroad will not affect health tax 
rates, so Western seniors who come to Israel after pension age should 
have nothing to fear by going to Bituach Leumi.  Young Western pensioners 
who arrive before their pension years, will have to go into 
Bituach Leumi to arrange payments.<P>
<STRONG>Returning Residents:</STRONG>  If a returning resident is abroad 
under 5 years he/she will be able to get immediate coverage.  If abroad 
over 5 years he/she will most likely need to pay from the date of 
return to Israel but may not be able to get coverage for 6 months.  
Check this out with Bituach Leumi.<P>
<STRONG>Self-Employed:</STRONG>  Should coordinate their payments 
through Bituach Leumi just as they coordinated regular Bituach Leumi 
payments.<P>
<STRONG>Students & Yeshiva Students:</STRONG>  Will pay NIS 49.  
Unemployed wives and children of yeshiva students do not pay.<P>
<STRONG>Salaried Workers:</STRONG>  All workers have their health 
tax deducted automatically from their salaries.  They pay 3.1% on the 
first NIS 2000 and 4.8% on the next NIS 2,000 to NIS 16,000.<P>
Above information was compiled in February 1995.  Expect prices 
to increase.
</UL>
