<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Health Insurance</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG> Private Supplemental Health Insurance
</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center><P>




On January 1, 1995 the <A HREF="health.htm">National Health Insurance</A> Law went into effect.
While statutory  health care coverage including hospitalization now 
provides a basic basket of services for all citizens and residents, the 
demand for private supplemental health insurance has if anything increased. 
The 4 Kupot Holim (literally sick funds but in effect are similar to  
American HMO's) are reputed to provide adequate primary care (family 
practitioner and pediatrician) but do not allow freedom of choice for 
surgical care and easy access to top specialists for out-patient and 
ambulatory care.  People who pay privately tend to get quicker access to 
the most sought-after specialists.  To cope with this problem each of the 
Kupot have developed their own group supplemental programs.  These are 
relatively inexpensive and provide some coverage for private care.  
However, as elsewhere, you tend to get what you pay for, and the coverage 
is not total.  The only way to be sure of having maximum choice over 
<UL>
<LI>who will be providing the service such as surgery 
<LI>when it will be done
<LI>where (some private hospitals are not covered by the Kupot)
</UL>
is by purchasing full private supplementary health insurance such as the
programs marketed through <A HREF="http://www.aaci.org.il/insure.htm">AACINSURANCE.</A>  <p>

The description below is of the most popular program <I>Kaf HaKesef</I> - The
Silver Line, of the Israel Phoenix Assurance Co., Ltd.<P>


<B>Insurance period:</B> life<BR>
<B> Maximum age of entry:</B> 60<P>

<H3><U>Features</U></H3>
                     

1. Prevention <br>
  A bi-annual periodic examination starting after two years. <P>


2. Surgery<BR>      
This includes expenses connected with surgery including surgeon's fee,
anesthesiologist's fee, operating expenses including implants, 
pathological exam, private nurses, private hospitalization, ambulance to 
the hospital.  This gives you private level of care and most importantly 
the right to choose who performs surgery, when, and where.  Unlike the 
Kupot group supplemental programs, it will cover all or almost all expenses
involved.  The vast majority of the top surgeons in Israel will accept 
payment by the insurance company.  Otherwise the insurance company will
reimburse the insured up to the company table for maximum amount per
specific procedure. If the Kupat Holim pays for hospitalization the
insurance plan pays you a per day hospitalization payment equivalent to 
about half of the charge for hospitalization.   There is no deductible or 
co-payment for this part of the program.<P>



<H3><U>Options</U></H3>

3. Out-patient and ambulatory care <BR>

This includes visits to specialists and diagnostic services even if not
connected with surgery.  Co-payment of 20%.<P>

4.Implants/transplants and medical procedures which have not been 
performed in Israel<BR>
                                
Coverage for operating team fee, examinations, medications, laboratory
services, hospitalization costs, travel expenses abroad for the patient 
and a companion, costs of special medical air transportation if needed,
reasonable expenses for the stay abroad by the patient and companion, and
the costs of bringing a specialist from abroad for performing the 
transplant or for special treatment.  Total costs are covered up to 
$1,000,000 for implants/transplants and up to $100,000 for other medical 
procedures not performed in Israel. No deductible or co-payment.<P>

5. Alternative medicine       <BR>

Treatment in approved clinics for acupuncture, homeopathy, chiropractic
treatments, shiatsu, reflexology, osteopathy, clinical dietician, 
Alexander and Feldenkreis methods.
20% co-payment.<P>


<UL>
<LI>The insurance company is not obliged to accept a candidate under regular 
or any other conditions.  Pre-existing conditions are excluded.

<LI>There is a more expensive plan which covers general practitioners, family
doctors, pediatricians, fertility procedures, private deliveries, elective
hospitalization for diagnostic purposes, pharmaceuticals, etc.  

<LI>There are also less expensive plans which cover a fixed list of surgical
procedures.
  
<LI>Limited long-term care coverage may be added for a very low cost.


<LI>Rates are related to age.  The insurance company is not obliged to accept a
candidate under regular or special conditions.  Pre-existing conditions are
excluded.  The descriptions included here are for general interest and are 
not binding. The binding conditions are those specified in the policies.
</UL>

For more information including prices contact an AACINSURANCE agent or 
<A HREF="http://www.aaci.org.il/insure.htm">AACINSURANCE.</a>  <P>




AACI wishes to thank Steven Kelter for providing this article.  Steven
Kelter is an authorized AACINSURANCE agent.  He has practiced insurance
both in the U.S. and Israel. <BR>
He may be reached by email: <A HREF="mailto:kelter@pobox.com">kelter@pobox.com</A><p> 
regular mail:<BR>
<address>Goldfus & Assoc. <BR>
9A Diskin St. <BR>
5th Fl. 96440 <BR>
Jerusalem, Israel </address>
Phone: 972-2-5612223 or 972-2-5612224 <BR>
