<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Filing U.S. Tax Returns</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>OBLIGATION OF AMERICANS TO FILE US INCOME TAX RETURNS WHILE LIVING IN ISRAEL</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>February 1996</FONT></CENTER><P>
American tax law requires all citizens and permanent residents of the 
United States to file annual income tax returns and to pay any income 
tax or social security tax which may be due.  There is an exception for 
persons whose total gross income is so low that they would not have to 
file a Federal tax return even if they were living in the U.S.<P>
Since taxpayers permanently residing outside the United States are 
entitled to an exemption for up to $70,000 of earned income, many or 
most taxpayers do not owe any income tax.<P>
However, this exemption does not apply to social security tax so that 
self-employed persons and employees of American employers are required 
to pay social security tax on income which is exempt from income tax.<P>
The 70% exemption is only for income earned from employment or profit 
from an active business.  It does not apply to passive income such as 
interest on bank deposits, dividends, rents, etc.<P>
To sum up, most Americans residing in Israel should file annual American 
income tax returns although few of them will actually owe any tax.<P>
<HR WIDTH=20% ALIGN=center>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>AACI wishes to thank Yitzhak Heimowitz, Attorney at Law 
for writing this article.<dd>Mr. Heimowitz can be contacted: 
Tel:03-5601994  Fax:03-5605356<BR>64A Shenkin St, T.A. 61141</STRONG><BR>
</DL></UL>
