<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>AACI - Traveling Abroad</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo-sm.gif" WIDTH=394 HEIGHT=48><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>When You Want to Travel  Out of Israel</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>W</FONT>hat happens, when once you've made Aliyah to 
Israel, how do you  leave Israel for a temporary visit abroad?<P>
<STRONG>Passports\ Travel Documents</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>T</FONT>o prevent problems, make sure that both your 
Israeli passports\ travel documents, and American\Canadian passports 
are always up to date.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>I</FONT>f you are not yet an Israeli citizen, that is, 
3 months have not passed since you became an Oleh, make sure that you 
speak to your local Ministry of Interior to arrange an Israeli travel 
letter, "michtav maavar". In cases of EXTREME emergencies, airport 
officials at Border Police have been known to permit olim to leave on 
their Foreign Passport, but, officially, you must have a "michtav maavar"   
Once you become an Israeli citizen, arrange your first Israeli Travel 
Document. Keep it up to date.<P>
<STRONG>Army Exit Permit</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>rom the time that you become an Oleh, if you are 
eligible for the Army, make sure that you have arranged an Army Exit 
Permit, "heter yetziah", to leave the country.   Before you have served 
in the army, this must be arranged at the local Army Induction Office, 
"Lishkat Ha'Gius". After serving in the army, you must arrange your 
exit permit with your individual division. For some units, this pass 
is stamped in your passport and is good for the duration of 
the passport. If you have an extreme emergency, there is an Army 
Representative ("Netzigut Tzahal") at the Airport, Tel 03-9710111.<P>
<STRONG>"Chevrat Idud"</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>M</FONT>ake sure of the following information if you 
are amongst olim that have availed themselves of funds\loans from 
"Chevrat Idud".   Make sure that "Chevrat Idud" always has your current 
address.  Any change of address should always be sent to them.   When 
you apply to the Ministry of Interior for an Israeli Travel document or 
passport, " Chevrat Idud" is automatically informed.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>T</FONT>heir assumption, whether correct or not, is that 
you are leaving the country.  They will send you a Hebrew letter, 
saying that they understand that you are intending to exit Israel, and 
they are requesting that you come into their office closest to where you 
reside, to arrange either repayment or to provide guarantees for the loan. 
Even if you are not leaving the country, you must go into the office, 
otherwise, "Chevrat Idud" may take out a court order preventing you from 
leaving Israel. This court order can be revoked by a lawyer and is a 
complicated and costly procedure.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>O</FONT>ur recommendation to avoid problems is : For people 
who have taken out "Chevrat Idud" loans, approach them when applying for 
an Israeli travel document or passport. Do not ignore the letters 
from "Chevrat Idud" if you receive one.<P>


<STRONG>Travel Agent</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>F</FONT>ind your self a good, trust worthy Travel Agent. 
Try  Ophir Tours' <A HREF="ophir.htm">The AACI Travel Experience</A> for 
your convenience!<BR>
Arrange Travel Insurance!<P>
<STRONG>Foreign Currency</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>B</FONT>efore you leave, if you wish to take out dollars 
from your Foreign Currency Account, make sure that you bring your airline 
ticket and passports to the Bank. Check with your bank to see what the 
limit of dollars you can withdraw is. Remember, after your trip, if you 
wish to put dollars back into your account, an Oleh who travels overseas 
can deposit foreign cash in a "Patach" account for 10 days only from his 
date of return.   (However, you may deposit cash in "Patach" accounts 
within 45 days from your date of Aliyah.)<P>
<STRONG>Other Bits of Advice</STRONG><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>K</FONT>eep your old expired passports and all your 
documents as well as photo copies of them, as proof of exits and 
entrances to Israel, in case you leave, and want to inquire about 
freezing of rights.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>S</FONT>peak to your AACI Counselor if you would like 
to go over these details or to check if anything has changed.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>W</FONT>hen buying your tickets don't 
forget <A HREF="ophir.htm"> THE AACI TRAVEL EXPERIENCE OPERATED BY 
OPHIR TOURS</A>, great service with prices that are hard to beat.<P>
Have a nice trip! "Nisia Tova!"<P>
</UL>
<BOTTOMINSERT>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="http://www.jer1.co.il/cgi-bin/imagemap/aacimap"><IMG 
SRC="botmbutn.gif" border=0 ISMAP></A><P>

<center><font size=-2>
