http://www.aaci.org.il:80/kibbutz.htm 204.253.42.137 19970221215117 text/html 3994
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Friday, 21-Feb-97 23:48:34 GMT
Last-modified: Sunday, 15-Dec-96 11:35:19 GMT
Content-length: 3811
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo.gif" WIDTH=299 HEIGHT=104><HR>
<UL>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><EM><STRONG>Kibbutz Division</STRONG></EM></FONT></CENTER><HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center>
The National Kibbutz Committee of the AACI came into being about 25 years 
ago in an attempt to answer the needs of members who chose a rural and a 
collective lifestyle. As opposed to their city cousins, the kibbutz 
member's concerns had nothing to do with mortgages, professions, income 
tax, schools etc. since all these 
matters were handled by their respective kibbutzim.<P>

What kibbutz members wanted was to be associated with an oleh 
organization which gave additional impetus to his or her desire to 
live on a kibbutz and give further 
expression to their Zionism and Judaism.<P>

We make a special effort to work with those that are seriously 
considering the kibbutz way of life as a meaningful alternate and 
do our utmost in helping them adjust not only to this shared venture 
but if the necessity arises and the kibbutz is not the answer, then 
to find their place in the greater Israel society.<P>

To this end the Inter Kibbutz Committee periodicly publishes a 
'bulletin'. In addition, seminars, conferences and forums are held 
to discuss the burning issues of today such as:<OL>
<LI>Changes on the kibbutz
<LI>Religous Issues
<LI>Problems of the single kibbutz member
<LI>Ecology, energy and the environment
<LI>Equality of women.<P>
</OL>

This is only a brief outline of some of the issues covered. Our aim 
is to inform, educate and give guidance. We are not an alternative to 
the information that is given out by the shlichim of the various 
Zionist bodies, the Jewish Agency or the Kibbutz Movements. Instead, 
we give supplemental information based on all of us living on kibbutzim 
anywhere from five to over thirty years and representative of different 
kibbutz movements and ideology.<P>
FAQ
<OL>
<LI>Have all the kibbutzim reverted to family sleeping arrangements?
<LI>Can I work off the kibbutz?
<LI>What is the attitdue towards owning and operating private cars?
<LI>What about private funds?
<LI>What has happened in the field of education, mainly from grades 
one and higher?
<LI>On certain kibbutzim the dining room has been closed down, 
partially and fully. How does this affect community living?
<LI>Holiday celebrations, have they been affected?
<LI>How large are the apartments?
<LI>How has the recent health law affected the kibbutz?
<LI>Pensions on the kibbutz?
</OL>


This is but a few of the FAQ's that we get. We don't claim to have all 
the answers but we may be able to guide you. THERE'S NOTHING BETTER THAN 
TO EXPERIENCE KIBBUTZ LIFE.<P> 
<BOTTOMINSERT>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="http://www.jer1.co.il/cgi-bin/imagemap/aacimap"><IMG 
SRC="botmbutn.gif" border=0 ISMAP></A><P>

