<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Aliyah Innsurance Advisory Service</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<A NAME="TOP">
<BODY BACKGROUND="bgrnd.jpg" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="logo.gif" WIDTH=299 HEIGHT=104><HR>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>AIAS - Aliyah Insurance Advisory Service</I></B> </FONT></CENTER>
<HR WIDTH=60% ALIGN=center>
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>RECOGNIZING THE NEED</FONT></CENTER>
<P>

AACI, in establishing 
<A HREF="insure.htm"> AACINSURANCE</A>
, recognized the need for an advisory service on Insurance matters for prospective Olim. There are many insurance factors one must consider before making Aliyah. Such as, which policies to cancel, which are better than the Israeli policy, and what policies are  really need.
<P>

AACI, together with 
<A HREF="insure.htm">AACINSURANCE </A> 
and 
<A HREF=#TOP>RBI</A>
Brokerage, Inc., has created the Aliyah Insurance 
<A HREF=#TOP>Advisory Service</A>
(AIAS) to provide insurance information to those making or planning to make Aliyah.
<P>

The service will provide you with the following FREE services;
<UL>
<LI> An evaluation of the insurance policies you currently hold
<LI> Suggestions on what to do with such policies upon Aliyah 
<LI> Suggestions on what, if any, other policies you should consider purchasing prior to, or after Aliyah, both in North America and in Israel.
</UL>

A summary of the issues can be found below.
<P>

This service is available to Olim and members of the AACI and may be accessed by:
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=7>
<TR> 
<TD>Telephone:</TD> <TD>(201) 857-1466</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>Fax:</TD> <TD>(201) 857-1487</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD>E-Mail:</TD> <TD><A HREF=mailto:"paulw@hal.datalife.com">
paulw@hal.datalife.com </A></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P> 
Ask for Paul Wolf
<P><BR>


There are basically two categories of insurance policy:

 <UL>
<LI> Those which <FONT SIZE=+1><B>PROTECT</B></FONT> your property (Property & Casualty)
<LI> Those which <FONT SIZE=+1><B>PROTECT</B></FONT>your person (Life & Health)
</UL>
<BR>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Property & Casualty Policies</B></FONT></U><BR>
(Known in Israel as "Elementary Insurance")
<P>
<U>
<FONT SIZE=+1>THESE</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+2>PROTECT:</FONT></U><BR>
<B>Your Property risks</B> - Homeowners insurance and<BR> 
<B>Your Casualty risks</B> - Automobile or Liability Insurance.
<P>

This type of policy is purchased to insure a specific piece of property or liability. Therefore, such a policy is usually not continued once the property is sold, or the liability no longer exists. These policies are normally renewable each year and may be subject to adjustments in premium at each renewal.
<P>

<UL>Q: What should I do with my Property & Casualty Policies during the Aliyah process?</UL
<P>

Upon vacating your residence, cancel all homeowners policies. If you are keeping your home in North America you may need to insure the building. however, insuring the contents will depend on what is left in the house. Speak to your North American Agent about this.
<P>
Automobile policies should be canceled when selling or returning your car.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Life & Health Policies</B></FONT></U><BR>
These policies PROTECT you and your family in case of:
 <UL>
<LI> Death - Life Insurance
<LI> Sickness - Health Insurance
<LI> Disability - Disability & Long Term Care Insurance
</UL>


These policies are generally portable, and may frequently be purchased in one country and still cover you in another. In general they automatically continue <B>as long as the premium is paid.</B>
<P>

<UL>
<U><B>Q:	What do I do with these Policies when I make Aliyah ?</B></U>
</UL>


<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Life Insurance:</B></FONT></U>
 <UL>
<LI> When you purchase life insurance in North America, you will generally be asked whether or not you intend to live outside the United States or Canada. 
<LI> The premiums payable, under most Life Insurance policies are directly affected by where you intend to live. 
<LI> Many insurance companies will not issue a policy to someone who, at time of purchase, is not living nor intending to live in North America.
</UL>

However, if you do purchase a policy and then decide at some later stage to leave North America, the policy will normally not be invalidated. Some policies may have restrictions on place of residence, while the majority of policies are free from such restrictions. If you purchase a policy with no restriction and decide later to "make Aliyah" you will not jeopardize the policy and can continue to pay premiums from Israel.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Health Insurance:</B></FONT></U><BR>
Most health policies cover you for only 60 or 90 days when out of the country. The exact amount of time will vary according to insurer. Don't assume that "they will never know" - remember that the insurer may overlook time out of the country when the claim is small, BUT, when you have a large claim,
they may look for any reason not to pay the claim. All they need to do is ask for your passport and or ticket.
<P>

Get in writing (from your insurer) the exact details of any time or other limitation on your Health Care Coverage while you are outside of North America.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>World-Wide Health Policies:</B></FONT></U><BR>
There are health policies available which will cover you for private care, anywhere in the world. In Israel these policies will pay for a private doctor and hospital. They will also cover you for care in the United States, Canada or anywhere else you may decide to travel to have the care performed outside of Israel. 
<P>

You can apply for these policies at anytime - either prior to or post Aliyah.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Disablility Insurance</B></FONT></U><BR>
These policies are generally purchased in connection with a specific profession or employment. If your disability insurance can be continued after leaving a specific employer, you should check to see whether it covers you. Some of these policies may have a "war zone" exclusion, which may invalidate the policy in Israel. 
<A HREF="insure.htm">AACINSURANCE </A>
has found that the cost of such policies in Israel compare favorably with the equivalent policies in North America. We suggest that your current policy is checked by our 
<A HREF="#TOP">Advisory Service</A>
 to see whether your policy can be replaced by a new one purchased in Israel.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Long Term Care Insurance:</B></FONT></U><BR>
Most long-term care (nursing) policies, purchased in North America, will only pay benefits in North America. There are, however, a few policies that  will pay benefits anywhere in the world. Check with our 
<A HREF="#TOP">Advisory Service</A>
 for details of such policies.
<P>

<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Special Aliyah Coverage :</B></FONT></U>
<UL>
<LI>Shipping Insurance is available from 
<A HREF="insure.htm">AACINSURANCE </A>
 to cover your shipments which specialize in insuring Aliyah shipments. 
<P>
	<UL>
    <I>AACI can't pack your personal belongings or accompany 
	them ensuring their safe arrival to you in Israel. But we 
	can provide you with the peace of mind" so that  If 
	something does go wrong, you are well protected."</I>
     </UL>
<P>
<LI> You should also consider travel insurance for your accompanying baggage.
<LI>  Please remember that you are not covered by Israel's health insurance system until you arrive in Israel as an Oleh. Therefore you should ensure that you have adequate health coverage until that point of time.
</UL>


<U><FONT SIZE=+1><B>To sum it up :</B></FONT></U>
 <UL>
<LI> Your Property and Casualty policies can probably be canceled on relinquishing the property, but check with your agent or broker before doing so.
<LI> Life and Health Policies should always be reviewed by an insurance expert knowledgeable in insurance matters in both Israel and North America. 
</UL>


AACI and 
<A HREF="insure.htm">AACINSURANCE </A>
offers you as an Oleh this free service. We are pleased to offer the services of Paul Wolf,  of 
<A HREF="#TOP">RBI</A>
Brokerage inc., to help you with your insurance questions.
<P><BR>

